Context¶

We work in a mid-size IT help desk consultancy and our CEO has tasked us with helping the People&Talent team implement a company-wide survey around mental health for everyone, but with a special focus on tech roles.

Our Goal¶

We have been provided a dataset that contains mental health survey results across various years in order to get insights into how we can make a better survey and gather more insights from our employees.

We are looking at:

  • industry trends
  • patterns in the survey
  • insights around mental health in tech
  • and we ultimately, want to find ways to make better surveys in our company

Table summary¶

  • Survey: we can forget about this table, forever, and never look back. None of the data it contains will be missed. This is the sharknado of all database tables.
  • Question: This table can be used to understand the meaning of the recorded answers. This will require substantial manual work to identify valuable questions that can helps us separate the wheat from the chaff.
  • Answer: once we have selected the valuable questions, we will spend most of our time working with this table.
    • This table contains everything, all squashed into one column, without regard for our mental wellbeing. May Codd have mercy for our souls

# let's create a small utility that we will reuse extensively
def sql_peek(
    md_title: str, sql: str, limit: int = 100, print_sql: bool = False
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    renders a small table view of the provided query, with a nice markdown formatted header
    """
    query = f"{sql} LIMIT {limit};"
    df_ = pd.read_sql_query(query, conn)
    display(Markdown(md_title))
    if print_sql:
        display(Markdown("`" + query + "`"))
    display(df_.head(limit))
    display(Markdown("___"))

Checking for duplications¶

We believe that there are no repeated answers for a given year-user-question tuple. i.e. that users can only vote once per survey.

Let's just double check it, to be extra sure.

In [10]:
q_find_duplicates_answers = """
 SELECT SurveyID, QuestionID, UserID, COUNT(*) AS responses
 FROM Answer
 GROUP BY SurveyID, QuestionID, UserID
 HAVING responses > 1
 ORDER BY responses DESC
"""
sql_peek("### Finding duplicate answers", q_find_duplicates_answers, 10)

Let's move forward

A Deeper dive into the survey data¶

With over +230k answers spread across +100 unique questions, we will need to be careful when selecting the most optimal subset of questions to analyze.

We would like to have a small sample of the types of questions that this database contains, and a few of the answers provided. It would also be ideal if we could calculate or guess how is the spread of answers for each question (was it a yes/no question? was it multiple choice? was it free text?). As a bonus, we would also like to have the info for each of the years. Maybe a question was "yes/no" the first year, and got changed to a multiple choice the second year.

We can write a little tiny SQL query that will do all of these things, and maybe a bit more! Let's make a list of the features needed:

REQUIREMENTS

  1. IT MUST show a sample of the answers collected for each of the questions
  2. IT MUST NOT include invalid answers (in this database '-1' seems to be a special value indicating N/A)
  3. IT MUST include the question prompt as text
  4. IT MUST distinguish across years (question 3 in year 2014 is not the same as question 3 in year 2015).
    • Just because they reused the same text prompt, does not mean that the options/dropdown lists they gave to respondents were the same.
  5. IT SHOULD be able to infer the type of question it is, based on the spread of the answers (binary? multiple choice? free text?...)
  6. IT COULD sort answers so we can easily find them, padding with 0s would be great
  7. IT COULD print results in a format that's easy to read (tabulated? pivoted to columns?.. )

Sampling the answers¶

In [14]:
q_questions_with_sample_answers = """
   WITH padded_answers AS (select AnswerText,
                                   SurveyID,
                                   UserID,
                                   substr('000' || QuestionID, -3, 3) AS QuestionID
                            from Answer),
         valid_answers AS (SELECT AnswerText,
                                  UserID,
                                  QuestionID,
                                  SurveyID || '-' || QuestionID as survey_question
                           FROM padded_answers
                           WHERE AnswerText <> -1),
         first_x_answers AS (select AnswerText,
                                    survey_question,
                                    ROW_NUMBER() over (
                                        PARTITION BY survey_question
                                        ) answer_number
                             from valid_answers),
         first_10_answers AS (SELECT AnswerText, survey_question, answer_number
                              FROM first_x_answers
                              where answer_number <= 10
                              ORDER BY survey_question),
         pivot_first_10 AS (select survey_question,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 1 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS1,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 2 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS2,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 3 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS3,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 4 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS4,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 5 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS5,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 6 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS6,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 7 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS7,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 8 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS8,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 9 THEN AnswerText END)  AS ANS9,
                                   max(case when answer_number = 10 THEN AnswerText END) AS ANS10
                            from first_10_answers
                            group by survey_question),
         answer_ratio AS (SELECT QuestionID,
                                 survey_question,
                                 COUNT(DISTINCT AnswerText) AS uniq,
                                 COUNT(AnswerText)          AS total,
                                 100 * COUNT(DISTINCT AnswerText) /
                                 COUNT(AnswerText)          as uniq_percent
                          FROM valid_answers
                          GROUP BY survey_question),
         question_type AS (SELECT QuestionID,
                                  survey_question,
                                  uniq,
                                  total,
                                  uniq_percent,
                                  CASE
                                      WHEN QuestionID IN ('003', '050')
                                          THEN 'country'
                                      WHEN QuestionID IN ('004', '051')
                                          THEN 'us_state'
                                      WHEN uniq = 11 then 'zero-to-ten'
                                      WHEN uniq = 10 then 'one-to-ten'
                                      WHEN uniq = 5 then 'choose-from-5'
                                      WHEN uniq = 4 then 'choose-from-4'
                                      WHEN uniq = 3 then 'choose-from-3'
                                      WHEN uniq = 2 then 'binary'
                                      WHEN uniq_percent > 50 or uniq >= 40
                                          THEN 'freetext'
                                      ELSE 'choice' END AS Q_TYPE
                           FROM answer_ratio)
    SELECT pivot_first_10.survey_question,
           q.questiontext,
           qt.Q_TYPE,
           pivot_first_10.ANS1,
           pivot_first_10.ANS2,
           pivot_first_10.ANS3,
           pivot_first_10.ANS4,
           pivot_first_10.ANS5,
           pivot_first_10.ANS6,
           pivot_first_10.ANS7,
           pivot_first_10.ANS8,
           pivot_first_10.ANS9,
           pivot_first_10.ANS10
    FROM question_type qt
            INNER JOIN pivot_first_10 ON qt.survey_question = pivot_first_10.survey_question
            INNER JOIN Question q ON q.questionid = qt.QuestionID
    ORDER BY qt.survey_question ASC
"""

Chosing questions for our analysis¶

After a bit of time digging through the questions and answers, we created a small spreadsheet field_mapping.ods which contains:

  1. The list of selected questions we would like to analyze. And by exclusion, the list of questions we will drop.
  2. A rough classification for all the questions, which includes their:
    • timeframe (past, present or future)
    • topic (are they asking about demographics? employment? psychological safety? family? ...)
    • metric (what is being measured within those 2 dimensions)
  3. a short nickname that will help us identify it easily.
    • Let's agree that present_demographics_country is much more readable than question 3 and allows the reader to make an educated guess around what the topic of the question was.

Timeframe criteria¶

I marked questions as "PAST" if:

  • they explicitly ask about past events/employers
  • OR they include present AND past events/employers

PAST questions are about identifying someones background and experiences, not necessarily their current environment.

"PRESENT" questions for:

  • exclusively present situations (no past and no future)

"FUTURE" questions include:

  • future only
  • present and future

You can see a visual summary in fig 1. below:

Let's load the spreadsheet we created and use it to help pandas re-shape our data.

We want to:

  1. [x] Drop the questions we have chosen not to keep.
  2. [x] Rename the question IDs so we can move away from things like Question 3 and into something human readable like Question present_company_is_tech

def bucket_age(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    df = auto_pandas.buckets(df, "present demographics age", 20, 60, 5)
    return df


def bucket_gender(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    given the vast gender gap in tech fields, we will categorize all answers into 'male' and 'non-male'
    """
    new_field = "present demographics gender cishet male"
    df[new_field] = 0

    gender = df["present demographics gender"]
    df.loc[gender.str.lower() == "cishet male", new_field] = 1
    df.loc[gender.str.lower() == "male", new_field] = 1

    # Judgement call:
    # given the context, this is definitely the
    # answer of a cishet male that might have
    # strong feelings towards this question. probably...
    # let's mark it accordingly
    df.loc[gender.str.lower() == "I have a penis", new_field] = 1
    return df


def bucket_country(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    given the overpresence of US data let's categorize them into "US and Non-US"
    """
    new_field = "present demographics country usa"
    df[new_field] = 0

    gender = df["present demographics country"]
    df.loc[gender.str.lower() == "united states of america", new_field] = 1
    df.loc[gender.str.lower() == "united states", new_field] = 1
    return df


df_answers = bucket_age(df_answers)
df_answers = bucket_gender(df_answers)
df_answers = bucket_country(df_answers)

def categ_columns(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    categ = auto_pandas.categorise_column_ordered
    df = categ(
        df,
        question_translation[8],
        ["1-5", "6-25", "26-100", "100-500", "500-1000", "More than 1000"],
    )
    df = categ(
        df,
        question_translation[17],
        [
            "Very easy",
            "Somewhat easy",
            "Neither easy nor difficult",
            "Somewhat difficult",
            "Difficult",
            "Very difficult",
            "I don't know",
        ],
    )
    df = categ(
        df,
        question_translation[30],
        [
            "Very open",
            "Somewhat open",
            "Neutral",
            "Somewhat not open",
            "Not open at all",
            "Not applicable to me (I do not have a mental illness)",
        ],
    )

    df = categ(
        df,
        "present demographics age_buckets",
        [
            "under 20",
            "20-25",
            "25-30",
            "30-35",
            "35-40",
            "40-45",
            "45-50",
            "50-55",
            "55-60",
            "60 or over",
        ],
    )
    return df


df_answers = categ_columns(df_answers)

q_race = """
WITH race_white AS (
    SELECT SurveyID,
           SUM(CASE WHEN AnswerText <> '-1' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)
               AS VALID_ANS,
           SUM(CASE WHEN AnswerText IN ('White') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)
               AS WHITE,
           SUM(CASE WHEN AnswerText NOT IN ('White', '-1') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)
               AS NON_WHITE
    FROM Answer
    WHERE QuestionID = 89
    GROUP BY SurveyID
)
SELECT SurveyID, WHITE, NON_WHITE, 100 * WHITE / VALID_ANS AS PCENT
FROM race_white
GROUP BY SurveyID
"""
sql_peek("Questions with sample answers", q_race)

Hypothesis¶

Exploring Privilege¶

Question 85 reads:

"Overall, how well do you think the tech industry supports employees with mental health issues?")

We believe that question 85 can be used to find patterns in other important indicators.

We expect to find patterns around axes of privilege / matrix of oppression

This dataset does not cover many axis of oppression, but we will look into: race, sex, gender, and age

Conclusions¶

This analysis pertains to the anth7310/mental-health-in-the-tech-industry dataset that can be found on kaggle.

Dataset¶

It contains data around mental health in the IT industry, as collected on various yearly surveys (2014 and 2016-2019),

The dataset contains an over-representation of respondents from these demographic groups:

  • white, male
  • based or working in the US
  • between 25-40 years old

across a variety of companies (from solo/small businesses to large corporations)

This might not be a bias in the sampling strategy, but a reflection of the IT field in those spaces.

Revisiting our initial Expectations¶

Let's review the list of expectations/theories we started with and assess whether they can be rejected or they warrant further investigation.

This is the original list we had:

Privilege¶

The dataset includes various dimensions around privilege:

  • race
  • gender
  • age

Age¶

While we see that the majority of population spread between 25 and 40, we cannot find any evidence or correlation across any age group when it comes to mental health support within their company or the entire industry

Gender¶

In the male/non-male analysis, we see a large proportion of self-identified male population.

While we do not see any strong correlations across data with regards to gender, it's important to keep in mind this over-representation in case it skews results for everyone else, if we were to look at overall averages.

Race¶

If the male/non-male analysis shows an over-representation, the race breakdown (both, across years, and also in general terms) shows a total eclipse of white people over everyone else, with ratios between 84-90% depending on the year.

Non-white respondents include 9 other groups and their second most common answer is "I prefer not to answer", which raises questions around psychological safety of the responders, maybe worrying about being outed if their answers were to be available to their employers.

Diagnostics¶

The only insights in this category are both unsurprising and positive but weak:

  • People who sought treatment are correlated with people diagnosed. Since this is almost a requirement, the interesting thing with this dataset might be in the negative space, more than the correlation itself.

Obviously people who were diagnosed, sought treatment, but the low correlation seems to indicate that most people who sought diagnosis/treatment, did not get diagnosed. Which makes sense. A high correlation here could indicate a problematic dataset (maybe with a strong bias around selection)

  • most people who got diagnosed have a family history of mental health disorders.

This is also not surprising, given what we know about some hereditary conditions. It would be good to compare these rations/correlations with broader studies to determine if this dataset is above/below population averages.

Pyschological Safety¶

When exploring people who got a diagnosis vs none, we saw that people who did are generally more open to sharing their journey with families and friends.

The meta analysis also included hypothesis around safety in the workplace.

The lack of company information makes it difficult to detect which companies might be suffering from a lack of psychological safety among their staff (intentional or not), and means to address it/notify them.

Executive Summary¶

Our company is considering implementing a survey like this one across IT/tech employees.

Here are some things we could do to get more useful insights.

  1. Being aware of industry-wide trends and biases:
    • so we can craft questions that include everyone
  2. Assessing Psychological Safety so it can be acted/improved.
    • Some questions might benefit from being optional, or allowing "I don't know" answers.

Assessing Safety¶

In the dataset, we can see a few examples of questions defaulting to "middle score" (3 stars out of 5) when:

  • The questions is mandatory
  • "I don't know" options are not available,
  • and the topic might be sensitive, or there is a fear of retaliation (low psych safety)

Perhaps the more interesting insights for individual companies might come from how many people respond with a non-answer (i don't know, blank, etc...) to identify which departments have lower safety scores.
